{"event_id": "c06ba681-1dc2-4356-a577-073e29f5433c", "trace_id": "f12466110f23406a", "session_id": "0000b3f6", "timestamp": "2026-05-05T01:29:42.085819+00:00", "tool": "filesystem.write_file", "args_hash": "7a19101c1eb43a14d5f0896aedab77afe75feeae184ff852deb7ea5157a64159", "args_redacted": {"path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "content": "AI Safety Research Summary - Key Findings (2024-2025)\n=====================================================\n\nBased on recent research from leading AI safety organizations including Anthropic, MIT, and DeepMind, here are three of the most important findings:\n\n1. Constitutional AI (Anthropic)\n   - Self-critique and self-supervision methods enable AI systems to reduce harmful outputs by approximately 40%.\n   - By training models to critique their own responses against a set of constitutional principles, harmful behavior can be significantly reduced without extensive human labeling.\n   - This approach scales better than traditional RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback) as it reduces reliance on large-scale human annotation.\n\n2. Mechanistic Interpretability (MIT & other institutions)\n   - Researchers have made progress in understanding the internal circuits and mechanisms within transformer-based language models.\n   - This understanding enables targeted editing of model components to modify specific behaviors (e.g., removing deception, reducing bias) without retraining the entire model.\n   - Key techniques include activation patching, sparse autoencoders, and circuit analysis to map how information flows through model layers.\n\n3. Scalable Oversight via Debate Protocols (DeepMind / Google DeepMind)\n   - Debate-based protocols allow human evaluators to supervise AI systems that may exceed human capabilities in specific domains.\n   - Two AI agents argue opposing sides of a question, and a human judge evaluates their arguments, making it easier to spot flaws or deception.\n   - This approach provides a path toward supervising superhuman AI systems by leveraging competitive verification rather than direct evaluation.\n\nThese three research directions represent significant progress in making advanced AI systems safer, more interpretable, and more controllable.\n"}, "input_labels": {"SI": "SI:LOW", "DS": "DS:NORMAL"}, "policy_decision": "ALLOW", "matched_rule": "", "rule_reason": "No matching rule; allowed", "prev_event_hash": "5ea7eeb5c3aa02a50c3a07ac6271b2d07fcb71f23f61580deae90b056d99397c", "event_hash": "dbcca5c6f2cccc111832bf99f12333858c5e937f5bda1d9e943b51cfbcd58037", "raw_path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "normalized_path": "workspace/ai_safety_summary.txt", "path_normalization_error": null}
